Knex can be used as an SQL query builder in both Node.JS and the browser, limited to WebSQL’s constraints (like the inability to drop tables or read schemas). Composing SQL queries in the browser for execution on the server is highly discouraged, as this can be the cause of serious security vulnerabilities.
What is Knex.js?
Knex.js is a SQL Query Builder for Node.js.
For example, instead of writing this raw SQL:
SELECT * FROM users WHERE age > 18;You write this in JavaScript:
knex('users').where('age', '>', 18);Knex converts it to SQL behind the scenes. Clean and simple.
Why Do We Need Knex.js?
Let me ask you something. Have you ever written a raw SQL query in Node.js using the mysql or pg package?
It looks something like this:
db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '" + name + "'", (err, results) => {
// handle results
});This is risky. Very risky.
If someone passes a bad value in name, they can break your database. This is called SQL Injection. It is one of the most common attacks on websites.
Knex.js protects you from this. It uses parameterized queries automatically. You don’t have to think about escaping strings or sanitizing inputs.
Also, Knex makes your code readable. You can chain methods. You can reuse query parts. You can switch databases without rewriting all your queries.
Tip: Always prefer query builders or ORMs over raw string concatenation for SQL. Your future self will thank you.
What is an SQL Query Builder?
An SQL Query Builder is a library that lets you create SQL queries using a programming language instead of writing SQL directly.
It is not an ORM.
An ORM (like Sequelize or Prisma) maps your database tables to JavaScript classes and objects. You work with objects. The ORM handles the SQL.
A Query Builder (like Knex) does not give you models or classes. You still write queries. But you write them in JavaScript, not SQL strings.
You have more control with a query builder. You can see exactly what SQL is being generated. You can tweak it easily.
Features of Knex.js
Here is what Knex gives you out of the box:

• Query Builder for SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE

• Transaction support for running multiple queries together

• Migrations for managing database schema changes

• Seed files for inserting test data

• Schema Builder for creating tables and columns

• Connection pooling for better performance

• Promise-based API with async/await support

• Raw SQL support when you need something custom

• Query events and debugging hooks
Supported Databases
Knex.js supports many databases:
Press enter or click to view image in full size

You install the driver for your database separately. Knex does not include them.
Installing Knex.js
Open your terminal and run these commands:
# Create a new project folder
mkdir knex-demo
cd knex-demo# Initialize package.json
npm init -y
# Install Knex
npm install knex
# Install your database driver (example for MySQL)
npm install mysql2
# For PostgreSQL, use:
# npm install pg
# For SQLite, use:
# npm install sqlite3
Setting Up a New Project
Create a folder structure like this:
knex-demo/
├── knexfile.js
├── db.js
├── migrations/
├── seeds/
└── app.jsCreating and Understanding knexfile.js
The knexfile.js is where you tell Knex how to connect to your database.
Create a file named knexfile.js in your root folder:
// knexfile.jsmodule.exports = {
development: {
client: 'mysql2',
connection: {
host: '127.0.0.1',
port: 3306,
user: 'your_db_user',
password: 'your_db_password',
database: 'your_database_name'
},
migrations: {
directory: './migrations'
},
seeds: {
directory: './seeds'
}
},
production: {
client: 'mysql2',
connection: {
host: process.env.DB_HOST,
user: process.env.DB_USER,
password: process.env.DB_PASSWORD,
database: process.env.DB_NAME
},
pool: {
min: 2,
max: 10
}
}
};
What is happening here?

• client tells Knex which database you are using.

• connection has your database login details.

• migrations and seeds tell Knex where to find those files.

• pool controls how many connections to keep open.
Note: In production, always use environment variables for passwords. Never hardcode them.
Connecting to the Database
Create a db.js file:
// db.js
const knex = require('knex');
const config = require('./knexfile');const environment = process.env.NODE_ENV || 'development';
const db = knex(config[environment]);
module.exports = db;
Now you can import db.js anywhere in your project and run queries.
CRUD Operations
CRUD means Create, Read, Update, Delete. These are the four basic operations you do on any database.
Create Operations :
const db = require('./db');async function createUser() {
const [id] = await db('users').insert({
name: 'Rahul Sharma',
email: 'rahul@example.com',
age: 25
});
console.log('New user ID:', id);
}
createUser();
What is happening?

• db('users') tells Knex to work with the users table.

• .insert() adds a new row.

• It returns the new row’s ID.
Read/Select Operations:
async function getAllUsers() {
const users = await db('users').select('*');
console.log(users);
}async function getUserById(id) {
const user = await db('users')
.where('id', id)
.first(); // returns only one row
console.log(user);
}
getAllUsers();
getUserById(1);
What is happening?

• .select('*') gets all columns.

• .where('id', id) filters rows.

• .first() gives you a single object instead of an array.
Update Operations :
async function updateUser(id) {
const count = await db('users')
.where('id', id)
.update({
age: 26,
updated_at: new Date()
}); console.log('Rows updated:', count);
}
updateUser(1);
What is happening?

• .update() changes the matching rows.

• It returns how many rows were updated.
Delete Operations :
async function deleteUser(id) {
const count = await db('users')
.where('id', id)
.del(); console.log('Rows deleted:', count);
}
deleteUser(1);
What is happening?

• .del() deletes matching rows.

• It returns how many rows were deleted.
Query Chaining
The best thing about Knex is that you can chain methods.
const users = await db('users')
.where('age', '>', 18)
.andWhere('status', 'active')
.select('id', 'name', 'email')
.orderBy('name', 'asc')
.limit(10);Where Clauses
Knex gives you many ways to filter data:
// Simple equality
db('users').where('id', 5);// Greater than
db('users').where('age', '>', 18);
// Multiple conditions (AND)
db('users').where({
status: 'active',
role: 'admin'
});
// OR condition
db('users')
.where('role', 'admin')
.orWhere('role', 'moderator');
// WHERE IN
db('users').whereIn('id', [1, 2, 3]);
// WHERE BETWEEN
db('users').whereBetween('age', [18, 30]);
// Raw condition
db('users').whereRaw('age > ? and status = ?', [18, 'active']);
Tip: Use .where() for simple filters. Use .whereRaw() only when you need something complex that Knex does not support directly.
Sorting and Limiting Results
// Order by name ascending
db('users').orderBy('name', 'asc');// Order by multiple columns
db('users').orderBy([
{ column: 'age', order: 'desc' },
{ column: 'name', order: 'asc' }
]);
// Limit results
db('users').limit(10);
// Skip first 20, get next 10 (for pagination)
db('users').offset(20).limit(10);
Joins
Joins let you combine data from multiple tables.
// Inner Join
const orders = await db('orders')
.join('users', 'orders.user_id', 'users.id')
.select('orders.*', 'users.name as user_name');// Left Join
const orders = await db('orders')
.leftJoin('users', 'orders.user_id', 'users.id')
.select('orders.*', 'users.name as user_name');
// Multiple joins
const data = await db('orders')
.join('users', 'orders.user_id', 'users.id')
.join('products', 'orders.product_id', 'products.id')
.select(
'orders.id',
'users.name as customer',
'products.name as product'
);
What is happening?

• .join() matches rows from both tables.

• .leftJoin() keeps all rows from the first table even if there is no match.

• You can rename columns with as to avoid conflicts.
Transactions
A transaction means “all queries succeed together, or all fail together.”
Imagine you are transferring money from one account to another. You need to:

• Deduct money from Account A

• Add money to Account B
If step 1 passes and step 2 fails, money disappears. That is bad.
Transactions fix this.
async function transferMoney(fromId, toId, amount) {
const trx = await db.transaction(); try {
await trx('accounts')
.where('id', fromId)
.decrement('balance', amount);
await trx('accounts')
.where('id', toId)
.increment('balance', amount);
await trx.commit();
console.log('Transfer successful');
} catch (error) {
await trx.rollback();
console.log('Transfer failed. Rolled back.');
throw error;
}
}
What is happening?

• db.transaction() starts a transaction.

• You use trx instead of db for all queries inside.

• trx.commit() saves everything.

• trx.rollback() undoes everything if something goes wrong.
Tip: Always use transactions when you are doing multiple related writes. It keeps your data safe.
Raw SQL Queries
Sometimes Knex cannot do what you need. In those cases, use raw queries.
// Simple raw query
const result = await db.raw('SELECT * FROM users WHERE age > ?', [18]);// Raw in a builder query
const users = await db('users')
.where(db.raw('age > ?', [18]))
.select('*');
// Raw for complex expressions
const stats = await db.raw(`
SELECT
COUNT(*) as total,
AVG(age) as average_age
FROM users
WHERE created_at > ?
`, [new Date('2024-01-01')]);
Warning: Only use raw queries when necessary. You lose the safety of parameterized queries if you are not careful.
Migrations
Migrations are like version control for your database schema.
They let you create tables, add columns, and modify structure in a safe, repeatable way.
Creating a Migration
Run this command:
npx knex migrate:make create_users_tableThis creates a file in your migrations/ folder:
// migrations/20240101120000_create_users_table.jsexports.up = function(knex) {
return knex.schema.createTable('users', (table) => {
table.increments('id').primary();
table.string('name', 255).notNullable();
table.string('email', 255).unique().notNullable();
table.integer('age').unsigned();
table.enum('status', ['active', 'inactive']).defaultTo('active');
table.timestamps(true, true); // created_at and updated_at
});
};
exports.down = function(knex) {
return knex.schema.dropTableIfExists('users');
};
What is happening?

• up() runs when you apply the migration. It creates the table.

• down() runs when you rollback. It removes the table.

• table.increments('id') creates an auto-incrementing primary key.

• table.timestamps(true, true) adds created_at and updated_at automatically.
Running Migrations
# Run all pending migrations
npx knex migrate:latest# Rollback last batch
npx knex migrate:rollback
# Check status
npx knex migrate:status
Seed Files
Seeds are for inserting test or default data into your database.
npx knex seed:make 01_usersThis creates a seed file:
// seeds/01_users.jsexports.seed = async function(knex) {
// Delete existing data first
await knex('users').del();
// Insert new data
await knex('users').insert([
{ name: 'Rahul', email: 'rahul@test.com', age: 25 },
{ name: 'Priya', email: 'priya@test.com', age: 28 },
{ name: 'Amit', email: 'amit@test.com', age: 30 }
]);
};
Run seeds with:
npx knex seed:runSchema Builder
Knex lets you create and modify tables without writing raw SQL.
// Create a table
await knex.schema.createTable('posts', (table) => {
table.increments('id');
table.string('title').notNullable();
table.text('content');
table.integer('user_id').unsigned().references('id').inTable('users');
table.timestamp('published_at');
table.timestamps(true, true);
});// Add a column
await knex.schema.table('users', (table) => {
table.string('phone').unique();
});
// Rename a column
await knex.schema.table('users', (table) => {
table.renameColumn('name', 'full_name');
});
// Drop a column
await knex.schema.table('users', (table) => {
table.dropColumn('phone');
});
// Drop a table
await knex.schema.dropTableIfExists('posts');
